[Patient] What foods should I eat to help manage my heart failure?
[Educator] Try eating more fruits, veggies, whole grains, and lean proteins to support your heart health.
[Patient] Can I still enjoy my favorite cultural dishes?
[Educator] You can modify traditional recipes by using less salt and choosing healthier cooking methods.
[Patient] I find it hard to give up salty snacks. Any tips?
[Educator] Try swapping salty snacks for unsalted nuts or seeds, popcorn, or fresh fruit for a healthier option.
[Patient] How can I make sure I'm getting enough protein in my diet?
[Educator] Include lean sources of protein like chicken, fish, beans, or tofu in your meals.
[Patient] Are there any specific foods I should avoid?
[Educator] Limit high-sodium foods like processed meats, canned soups, and salty snacks to manage your heart failure.
[Patient] I'm not sure how to cook healthier meals. Any suggestions?
[Educator] Look for heart-healthy recipes online or consider taking a cooking class to learn new techniques.
[Patient] Can I still enjoy desserts while managing my heart failure?
[Educator] Opt for fruit-based desserts or small portions of dark chocolate to satisfy your sweet tooth.
[Patient] How can I involve my family in making healthier meals?
[Educator] Encourage your family to join you in meal planning and preparation to make healthier choices together.
[Patient] I struggle with portion control. Any advice?
[Educator] Try using smaller plates, measuring portions, and listening to your body's hunger cues to manage portion sizes.